is father John on official journeys around the Colony and brought his first wife to live in the family house. EH wrote that he received from his father full information about the family's English origins — and that his father was the best informed of all Thomas Hooker's grandsons on the subject."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Three sisters married Hart brothers — knot tied","body":"His sisters Abigail, Mary, and Sarah each married a son of Capt. John Hart between 1719 and 1725. Through those three marriages, Roger found himself simultaneously brother-in-law to Nathaniel, Samuel, and Matthew Hart — the Hart and Hooker families fully intertwined."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"His granddaughter Abigail married Samuel Talcott","body":"His son Thomas Hooker fathered Abigail Hooker, who married Samuel Talcott of Hartford. The marriage merged the Hooker surname into the Talcott line — a transition that defines several gen 6+ branches."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Roger Hooker","first_name":"Roger","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"roger-hooker-1710"},"I00136":{"id":"I00136","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1720,"month":2,"day":19,"city":"Newington","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1797,"month":2,"day":17,"city":"Farmington","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"mother_research_notes":"Dorothy Chester","father_research_notes":"Capt. Martin Kellogg of Newington, Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00104","date_year":1747,"location_city":"Farmington","location_county":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1774,"children_ids":["H00304","H00305","H00306","H00307","H00308","H00309","H00310"]}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 104"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Anna Kellogg Hooker","first_name":"Anna","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":["Hooker"],"maiden_name":"Kellogg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"anna-kellogg-1720"},"H00030":{"id":"H00030","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":3,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1664,"month":2,"day":20,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1746,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00007","mother_id":"I00006"},"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 30"},{"short":"Native Northeast Portal","url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-john-1664-1746"},{"short":"L.J. Hooker 1898","full":"L.J. Hooker, 'Edward Hooker, Commander, U.S. Navy,' The Old Northwest Genealogical Quarterly (Columbus, Ohio, 1898-), VII, 12"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00031","children_ids":["H00095","H00096","H00097","H00098","H00099","H00100","H00101","H00102","H00103","H00104"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1687,"date_month":11,"date_day":24}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","notes":"Col. Wadsworth's son Daniel Wadsworth founded the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford — a monument with Hooker family kinship interest. Research needed to confirm Mehitable Russell's Hooker descent line. Warren 1887 confirms: Elizabeth Standley married John Wadsworth — their son Daniel Wadsworth founded the Wadsworth Atheneum.","related_id":"X00035","display_label":"was his father-in-law, honored in the Indian wars","link_text":"Capt. John Standley"},{"type":"civic_peer","notes":"Capt. Thomas Hart b. ca. 1644, d. Aug 27, 1726 age 82. Son of Stephen Hart (X00034). Brother of John Hart who survived the 1666 fire (X00033). Not in this tree through marriage — noted as civic context only.","related_id":"X00034","display_label":"helped govern Farmington alongside him for decades","link_text":"Stephen Hart"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"T00387","display_label":"married a descendant of both Hooker and Standley","link_text":"Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00418","display_label":"served Hartford’s founding-family public life alongside him","link_text":"Rev. Daniel Wadsworth"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"was his wife’s sister and Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth’s grandmother","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00031","display_label":"fathered four children who married four of his own","link_text":"Capt. John Hart"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"I00053","display_label":"Both served as Connecticut Colony Supreme Court judges.","link_text":"Hon. Daniel Edwards"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00089","display_label":"was the cousin whose Indian Neck deed he registered","link_text":"William Hooker"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00263","display_label":"signed a Tunxis dispossession deed as his descendant’s in-law","link_text":"Lt. John Mix"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00439","display_label":"shared his entanglement in Tunxis affairs, decades apart","link_text":"Ezekiel Cowles Jr."},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00045","display_label":"was called with him one of Farmington’s two prominent men","link_text":"Captain Thomas Hart"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington, Hartford County, Connecticut. Same cemetery as his father Rev. Samuel Hooker (H00007)."},"gender":"male","tags":["politician","judge","compiler_ancestor"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Connecticut Superior Court judge, 1724-1732","primary_url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-john-1664-1746","primary_url_label":"Native Northeast Portal — John Hooker biography"},"documents":["DOC004"],"residence":{"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"law","header":"Judge of Connecticut Colony's Supreme Court","body":"He served as Judge of the Supreme Court of Connecticut Colony from 1724 to 1732 and as Speaker of the Lower House. He also served as witness, certifying Assistant, and Registrar in the 1733 Sue Squa land deed — three official roles in a single transaction."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"He defended Tunxis land rights in court","body":"In 1738, John Hooker provided a formal statement to the Connecticut General Court that ninety acres at Indian Neck had 'always belonged' to the Tunxis tribe — an unusual act of testimony on behalf of the indigenous people whose land his own ancestors had settled near."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"The elm fell so someone could walk straight","body":"His father gave him a site on the west side of Farmington's main street, where he built under the branches of a great elm. The tree became famous through all the region for the company that gathered beneath it — three generations of Hookers lived in its shade before a later owner cut it down to straighten the sidewalk."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"The bell tolled — Hooker stepped out first","body":"A chronicler recorded that every Sunday the bell rang, then began tolling; at the first stroke, Hooker issued from his house and proceeded to the Meeting House. The minister walked from his house. Whoever arrived first waited at the door; together they entered — at which the bell stopped and all the congregation arose."},{"number":5,"category":"character","header":"The Sabbath ended when Hooker touched his gate","body":"The holiness of Sunday was supposed to end at sunset — but no child in the town dared stir until John Hooker gave the signal. When the sun sank, he walked to his gate and leaned on it; open flew the doors and out came the children with a wild rush and shout."},{"number":6,"category":"character","header":"Dark hair, dark eyes — dignity commanding respect","body":"His grandson described him: \"Dark hair and dark eyes, and a dignity in his air and expression that procured profound respect.\" A fine looking man, tall, very erect, and had a prominent large nose. He lived his entire life in Farmington, dying there in 1746 at age 81."}],"career":[{"role":"Justice and Register","organization":"Farmington, Connecticut","notes":"Served as justice and register of Farmington"},{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Court","notes":"From Farmington. Served as Clerk two sessions; Speaker six sessions."},{"role":"Speaker","organization":"Connecticut General Court Lower House"},{"role":"Assistant","organization":"Colony of Connecticut"},{"role":"Judge, Superior Court","organization":"Colony of Connecticut","notes":"Served as judge of Superior Court concurrent with assistant role"},{"role":"Commissioner, Mohegan Sequestered Land","organization":"New London, Connecticut","notes":"Commissioner of the Mohegan's sequestered land at New London"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Hon. John Hooker","title":"Honorable","first_name":"John","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-hooker-1664"},"I00031":{"id":"I00031","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1669,"month":7,"day":25,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1743,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00030","children_ids":["H00095","H00096","H00097","H00098","H00099","H00100","H00101","H00102","H00103","H00104"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1687,"date_month":11,"date_day":24,"location_country":"United States"}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entries 99-101"}],"parents":{"father_id":"X00035","mother_id":"X00036"},"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_marriage","related_id":"I00051","display_label":"Both married Hooker brothers — from two separate Stanley families.","link_text":"Mary Standley"},{"type":"founding_family_nexus","related_id":"X00032","display_label":"Their families united — three daughters married Hart brothers.","link_text":"Mary Moore Hart"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"Her sister Elizabeth Standley married into the Wadsworth line.","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her father won distinction in the Indian wars","body":"Capt. John Standley was a man of wealth and high social position who had served as lieutenant and captain in the Indian wars. Her sister Elizabeth Standley's granddaughter married Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth, Commissary General of the Continental Army — Wadsworth's wife also descended from Rev. Thomas Hooker, making Wadsworth's children doubly connected to the Hooker line."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Abigail Standley Hooker","notes":"Also spelled 'Stanley' in EH entry 30; 'Standley' in entries 99-101","first_name":"Abigail","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":["Hooker"],"maiden_name":"Standley"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington CT. SOURCE: FindAGrave."},"slug":"abigail-standley-1669"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}